               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450512-name-973" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-973" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-973" type="surname" value="BERRIDOE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-973" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BERRIDOE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a coal-merchant, and live in Vauxhall-street. On the 12th of May, about half-past seven o'clock in the evening, I was in Greenwich fair—an officer touched me on the shoulder, and I found that I had lost two handkerchiefs—the one that was found on the prisoner Manyon I had wiped my face with a few minutes before—this is the same pattern as the one I had—I do not know it by any mark—I have every reason to believe it is mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450512-name-974" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-974" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-974" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-974" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WHITE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 180.) I was in Greenwich fair—I saw the two prisoners in company—they went and closed behind the prosecutor, and I saw Manyon lift the tail of his coat—I did not see them take the handkerchief, but I suspected them, and spoke to the prosecutor</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184505120188"></xptr>
               <p>—he said he had lost something—I went and took the prisoner—Manvon I said, "I have stolen the gentleman's handkerchief"—he put his hand into the flap of his trowsers, and took out this handkerchief—the prosecutor said, "That is not mine"—I took the prisoners to the station, and I fonud in Manyon's waistcoat this other handkerchief, which the prosecutor does identify.</p>
               <p>
